<TEXT>
homesick and heartsick over the iraqi invasion of their country 
stranded kuwaiti students are doing more worrying than studying 
and some have dropped out to join the fight 
studying comes second now said osamah altuwairesh one of 
14 kuwaiti students at the university of southern california last 
semester the first thing we think about is getting our country 
back 
students and other kuwaiti nationals began gathering in 
washington dc on friday for a conference to discuss their 
countrys situation the meeting expected to draw up to 1500 
people ends on sunday 
ever since the first day of august all my friends have talked 
about going back and joining the resistance said altuwairesh 
president of the 110member southern california branch of the 
national union of kuwaiti students he said he knows at least a 
dozen students who have traveled to saudi arabia since the invasion 
the first day this happened some students started collecting 
names of people saying they were ready to go said abdulhamid 
khudada a graduate architectural engineering student at penn 
state thats the least we could do its not fair the americans 
and others go to fight for our country and we dont fight 
the kuwaiti embassy has tried to encourage the more than 1200 
students at us universities and colleges to stay in school 
despite possible financial hardships caused by a cutoff of funds 
from their oilrich government which had supplied many with 
scholarships and living stipends 
they dont want people just to back there and get killed 
altuwairesh said the students really dont have any military 
training 
the embassy is working on ways to pay the students bills and 
many schools have agreed to defer tuition dormitory and book costs 
for the moment others are offering loans and helping the kuwaitis 
find jobs the immigration and naturalization service is allowing 
them to work 20 hours a week during the crisis 
the university did everything possible to help said 
univeristy of new mexico architecture student jamal alhajji 
they told me if you want a job in school we can arrange it for 
you and they can give me a loan 
central michigan university also has agreed to defer payments 
for its 15 kuwaiti students said sharon george director of the 
international student services in return the kuwaiti students 
are very very thankful she said they are a gracious people 
and a proud country they are not used to being cared for 
saif abdullah of the kuwaiti embassy in washington said they are 
collecting donations and have reduced the usual stipends by about 
40 percent the students will go through some hardship until 
everything is ok he said 
but financial worries pale next to family ones many students 
have not heard from relatives since the aug 2 invasion 
im so worried said saud abdullaziz a senior at the 
university of san francisco who last spoke to his parents and 
brother in kuwait city the day before the iraqis moved in im 
thinkng of canceling this semester and going back to check on my 
family i am just thinking all the time about home 
anwar almudhat a doctoral candidate in finance and investment 
at claremont graduate school said his fellow students can do more 
for their country by staying here than by returning home 
its a noble thing to do but most of these people arent 
trained almudhat said besides we need these people here in 
the united states to present our peoples case to case to the 
american public and this by itself is a noble thing 
</TEXT>
