<TEXT>
japans reaction to the persian gulf crisis reveals 
a nation still not ready to take on the responsibilities of global 
leadership despite its status as an economic superpower 
prime minister toshiki kaifu announced wednesday nearly one 
month after the iraqi invasion of kuwait an aid package of nearly 
1 billion for the usled force arrayed against iraq and further 
assistance to middle east countries hurt by the embargo on baghdad 
robert orr director of the stanford japan center in kyoto says 
japans policy formulation was largely a matter of deciding what 
could be done to placate washington 
i dont think thats the way a great power should be 
operating orr said friday the japanese still really do not 
have a global perspective 
japanese bureaucrats can expect further pressure from the united 
states which had applauded the package as an initial contribution 
to the gulf forces washington has urged tokyo to provide 
transportation for military cargo 
the iraqi invasion of kuwait on aug 2 has shown that the 
japanese political system is illequipped to cope with the quick 
decisionmaking required in responding to international crises 
bureaucratic infighting between powerful ministries has made it 
difficult to reach a consensus a cherished goal of political life 
here 
in effect they were arguing when they should have taken 
action the japan times newspaper said in an editorial 
and kaifu despite strong showings in public opinion polls does 
not have the power base within the governing liberal democratic 
party to easily push through his own agenda 
throughout the process of determining its contribution to the 
middle east japan has never made clear what its basic policy 
is the newspaper mainichi shimbun wrote friday 
kaifu has acknowledged the countrys growing responsibility 
in the world and awareness of growing impatience with the pace of 
tokyos response 
if our response was delayed any further i was afraid we would 
give the impression to the world that japan is not doing anything 
about this serious problem he said after unveiling the package 
behind the weeks of waiting for a japanese aid program to emerge 
was a heated debate over what could be done under the postworld 
war ii constitution that bars the use of force in settling 
international disputes 
there is strong public opinion in japan and throughout asia 
against any action that could lead to japanese military activity 
overseas 
triggered by the us pressure bureaucrats and politicians are 
debating a change of the countrys laws that would make it easier 
for japan to respond to future crises in a decisive matter but 
which critics charge could led to a violation of the constitution 
a government official speaking on condition of anonymity said 
the legal review was unprecedented and indicates that japans 
reaction to the middle east tension is charting new ground for the 
country 
any proposed revisions are sure to meet with strong opposition 
in the parliament where the japan socialist party is the largest 
opposition group 
a senior socialist recently said of the crisis it is an ideal 
time for japan to show the spirit of our peace constitution 
</TEXT>
