<TEXT>
the idea of a floating hospital for injured 
seals and sea lions seemed like a good one to dan deuel and mary 
crumley but it smacked of harboring the enemy to some people who 
have made death threats against the couple 
man is pretty possessive said neal langbehn a national 
marine fisheries service special agent whose job includes tracking 
down people who shoot marine mammals if a critter causes him any 
problems all his natural instinct seems to be to get rid of the 
critter as man takes up more and more of the earth there are 
going to be more conflicts 
deuel and crumley and some volunteers run free flight bird and 
marine mammal rehabilitation ltd from their home on a bluff 
overlooking the pacific ocean 
earlier this year deuel suggested to the bandon port commission 
that he could move his operation to a barge in the harbor that 
would make it more accessible to the public and more mobile in case 
of an oil spill 
the commission said ok but the reaction from some nameless 
people was different 
my old man says you will be so ticked off when that mary gets 
dead just like our fish no barge or shes dead read one 
letter 
the mans voice on the telephone answering machine was choked 
with anger bring one sea lion into the port of bandon and ill 
kill him right along with you buddy 
the threats have been turned over to the oregon state police 
which called in the fbi to help 
they sound maybe crazy enough to do it crumley said 
if we get a death threat here we feel it is not just a death 
threat towards us said deuel it is a death threat against 
anyone who cares about peace on this planet 
free flight which deuel started 13 years ago is caring for an 
orphaned steller sea lion pup and three injured harbor seal pups 
one was shot one was attacked by a dog and one was hit by rocks 
thrown by children 
because of the hostility i dont release any of them around 
certain coastal communities deuel said 
the law allows fishermen to shoot harbor seals and california 
sea lions if they steal fish and wont be driven away but not 
steller sea lions they were listed this year as a threatened 
species because of dwindling numbers in alaskan waters 
though their population is stable in oregon a fisherman who 
shoots one here is still liable for a 25000 federal fine 
theres an awful lot of hard feelings on the entire coast 
from california clear up to alaska about the seals and sea lions 
and their predation onto salmon said melvin erdman who has 
fished out of bandon for 48 years 
when a sea lion comes across a salmon troller it will dog the 
boat for hours taking the fish right off the hook as the fisherman 
winches it in 
bitterness runs deep among fishermen who have watched the 
government cut and complicate the salmon season to conserve 
dwindling stocks then protect a predator 
erdman said there is no shortage of people who would happily 
kill the seals and sea lions deuel and crumley care for though he 
hasnt heard anyone threaten the couple directly 
despite the threats deuel said he wont give up on his project 
it is all dependent on how our fund raising goes and right now 
it is not going too bad he said 
</TEXT>
