harmony between the two faiths although they see signs of 
potential conflict with fundamentalists favoring the imposition of 
the sharia or islamic law 
in burundi the popes visit will mark the end of conflict 
between church and state only three years ago all foreign 
missionaries had been expelled local priests detained weekday 
church services banned and religious education halted 
but since president pierre buyoya took power in a 1987 coup 
religious freedom has been restored and the church is working with 
the government to promote unity in a nation often torn by violence 
between the tutsi and hutu ethnic groups 
the pope will spend two nights each in burundi and rwanda before 
traveling across the continent to the west african nation of ivory 
coast where he will end his trip sept 10 by consecrating the 
basilica of our lady of peace 
the basilica modeled on st peters and nearly as large was 
built by president felix houphouetboigny in his hometown of 
yamoussoukro at a cost put by the government at 133 million the 
president says he is paying for the church with his own money 
but critics have charged the cost may be twice as high and 
described the basilica as a display of opulence in a poor country 
facing severe economic crisis 
the pope waited to consecrate the basilica until 
houphouetboigny agreed to build a hospital on the grounds 
vatican spokesman joaquin navarro said the holy see is not 
embarrassed by the basilica pointing out the money was not spent 
on weapons he also wondered why there was no similar outcry over 
the construction of mosques in morocco nigeria saudi arabia and 
rome that are even bigger 
