<TEXT>
gov george deukmejians plan to 
require california homeowners to pay up to 60 a year for mandatory 
earthquake coverage was approved by the legislature 
the bill was inspired by the october 1989 northern california 
quake that killed 62 people destroyed more than 1000 homes and 
caused 7 billion in damage it was sent to deukmejians desk 
friday evening after votes of 283 in the senate and 4321 in the 
assembly 
the bill would provide about 65 million property owners with up 
to 15000 of quake insurance for an annual surcharge of between 
12 and 60 
it would set up a statebacked insurance pool that would be used 
to partly recompense homeowners losses in the event of a quake it 
initially would provide up to 15000 in money that a homeowner 
would use to bridge the gap left uncovered by the average 
deductible 
quake insurance deductibles average about 10 percent of the 
market value of a home if a home is completely destroyed a 
customer can replace the house by meeting the cost of the 
deductible or about 15000 on a 150000 dwelling 
but most of the 24000 quakedamaged homes were not completely 
destroyed suffering an average of 8000 in losses each that was 
usually far less than the deductible and had to be paid by the 
homeowner 
deukmejian has 10 days to sign the bill veto it or let it 
become law without his signature 
