<TEXT>
boris n yeltsin populist president of the 
russian republic sharply criticized soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev saturday over plans to free the sinking economy of 
government control and let the market rule 
he rejected gorbachevs call of a day earlier for the merger of 
two vastly different blueprints for economic reform 
yeltsin told a news conference at the russian federation 
headquarters we wont go along with merging the two programs 
thats completely unrealistic that would be a brake not only on 
economic reform but also on the entire renewal of society and the 
political life of our country 
the president is showing indecisiveness in this regard he 
said 
one plan prepared by premier nikolai i ryzhkov calls for the 
government to retain control over prices initially and for 
longterm denationalization of industries and property 
the other drafted by a governmental advisory board outlines 
more rapid lifting of price controls and a quick switch to private 
control of most industries and private individual property 
yeltsin said the plan by stanislav shatalin a member of 
gorbachevs presidential council advisory group should be 
presented to the legislatures of the nation and the 15 republics 
the clash was the latest in a rocky threeyear relationship 
during which gorbachev kicked yeltsin out of the soviet leadership 
for blasting reform plans as too timid and yeltsin staged a 
political comeback based on widespread popular support 
a new poll taken in july by the national center for 
sociopolitical studies indicated that yeltsins popularity rose 
from 290 percent to 471 percent since last year and gorbachevs 
fell from 362 percent to 184 percent ryzhkovs rating fell from 
206 percent to 31 percent 
a report on the poll by the independent news agency interfax 
gave no margin of error nor did it say how the survey was 
conducted 
the latest dispute was a setback to the efforts of a 12member 
committee of leading economists assembled jointly by gorbachev and 
yeltsin in july to develop a common policy on economic reform 
gorbachev told a news conference friday night that the two plans 
must be merged into a document that reflects general agreement 
yeltsin believes the plans are so fundamentally different they 
cannot be combined he said shatalins plan would be presented to 
the russian supreme soviet at the session opening monday it 
closely follows a plan endorsed by yeltsin earlier 
the national supreme soviet convenes sept 10 
people are tired of waiting yeltsin said seated amid a sea 
of microphones in front of the blueandred russian republic flag 
people are at the limit of patience therefore they 
expressed such very sharp dissatisfaction with the actions of the 
union government which for five years did practically nothing in 
economic reform 
he said he got a sense of public reaction during a 
justcompleted 22day tour of 27 cities in the russian republic 
if the russian federation goes its own way on economic reform 
it would immensely complicate gorbachevs efforts to unify a 
country already fractured by ethnic conflicts yeltsins government 
already has moved to seize control of banking in russia from soviet 
authorities and he said it could start implementing an overall 
economic reform program on oct 1 
yeltsin believes ryzhkovs plan would maintain the central 
governments command system which he blames for aggravating the 
countrys economic problems if implemented it would lead to a 
collapse he said 
he said any plan adopted is doomed to fail unless ryzhkov and 
the ministers under him resign gorbachev himself is at risk 
yeltsin said 
every day the union government takes away from confirming this 
plan it diminishes gorbachevs term he said 
after government advisory bodies met for two days to discuss 
economic reform gorbachev said friday that the government will try 
to stabilize the faltering economy within six months by cutting off 
soviets ability to accumulate hot money that is the term for 
income derived from black marketeering and other activities 
ryzhkovs initial program presented in may and rejected by the 
national legislature a month later called for drastic price 
increases on bread and other items whose prices have remained 
basically unchanged for decades 
the program fueled panic buying that left illstocked store 
shelves even barer 
</TEXT>
