<TEXT>
california lawmakers rejected a 
proposal to move up californias presidential primary from june to 
march after stumbling over the issue of whether the primary ballot 
should be stripped of voter initiatives 
the planned shift would have put californias primary in the 
first week of march hard on the heels of the iowa caucuses and the 
new hampshire primary it failed to go to a vote late friday when 
assembly members rejected a constitutional amendment that would 
have stripped all other ballot measures from the presidential 
primary ballot 
a fragile compromise worked out by supporters of the early 
primary depended on legislative approval of both the amendment and 
the main bill but it fell apart just hours before the end of the 
1990 legislative session 
they may try to bring it back next year but i doubt it 
said sen ken maddy the senates gop leader and the author of the 
proposed amendment frankly i dont see a groundswell of support 
for it except from some insiders and political reporters 
supporters say the shift would change the california election 
from an afterthought into the nations dominant early primary 
now one of the latest in the nation the california primary 
hasnt had a real impact on a presidential nomination race since 
1972 when george mcgoverns victory here cleared the way for his 
democratic nomination 
the early primary proposal would have left a separate primary 
for congressional legislative and other races in june but under 
californias constitution voter initiatives that were ready would 
have to go on the same ballot as the presidential primary 
both parties were concerned that a onesided primary or one 
that drew especially strong voter interest for one party could 
skew the results of ballot proposals 
since initiatives in recent years have included major issues 
like the proposition 13 property tax cuts a cigarette tax hike and 
major insurance education and environmental measures that raised 
the possibility of major policy issues being decided principally by 
voters of only one party 
to avoid that maddy tied the early primary bill to enactment of 
a constitutional amendment that would bar initiatives from the 
presidential primary ballot 
but while the early primary bill required only a simple majority 
vote of the senate and assembly maddys constitutional amendment 
required a twothirds majority 
after several assembly roll calls the vote for maddys bill was 
47 to 25 seven short of the required majority in the 80seat lower 
house 
maddy said lawmakers were unsure about the effects of moving to 
a march primary even if his amendment had passed the lower house 
maddy said the assembly may have wanted to sit on the bill until 
next year 
the early primary proposal faced stiff opposition in the senate 
where the democratic leader president pro tem david roberti of los 
angeles opposed maddens constitutional amendment 
the problem is what to do with the initiatives roberti 
said he said he prefer leaving them on the ballot in march and 
november because thats when we will have the biggest turnout 
