<TEXT>
a federal appeals court friday refused to 
order the environmental protection agency to install new curbs on 
the precursors of acid rain to benefit canada 
the us circuit court of appeals for the district of columbia 
said the eap could study the issue further 
the case could be close to moot since congress is expected to 
order new measures against the precursors of acid rain chiefly 
sulfur and nitroggen oxides emitted by utility and other 
smokestacks in revisions to the clean air act expected to pass 
this fall the united states and canada have begun negotiations on 
a treaty to deal with the issue 
half of acid rain falling in eastern canada originates in the 
united states much of that from the industrial areas of the 
midwest and central atlantic states 
the province of quebec sued epa more than two years ago in an 
attempt to force the epa to act canada contents that 14000 of its 
lakes are endangered by acid rain which can turn lakes in 
sensitive soil areas so acidic that no fish can live 
just before president reagan took office outgoing epa 
administrator douglas costle wrote secretary of state edmund muskie 
that the us pollution in question was harming canada 
quebec supported by new brunswick ontario nine northeastern 
us states and several environmental groups argued in court that 
costles letter constituted a determination under us law that 
required action against offending pollution sources 
the us environmental agency countered that it was not trying 
to stall a pollution cleanup but needed more time to identify 
specific remedial actions and sources 
a threejudge panel of the appeals court agreed and said the 
agency had the right to wait until the completion of a massive 
scientific study on acid rain commissioned by congress 10 years 
ago the hundreds of scientists involved in the study are expected 
to release their final report in december 
the epas delay in action on the plaintiffs petitions has 
been neither arbitrary nor capricious nor contrary to law the 
court said in its ruling 
in us federal administrative law courts generally may 
overturn decisions in an agencys area of expertise only if those 
decisions can be shown to be arbitrary capricious or otherwise 
contrary to law 
