<TEXT>
a federal appeals court upheld the 
governments right to restrict payments of supplemental security 
income to aged and disabled people who have received overpayments 
from other programs 
by a 30 vote the 9th us circuit court of appeals overruled a 
decision by a san francisco federal judge who threw out the 
restrictions in nine western states the court agreed with four 
other federal appeals courts that have upheld the same rules in the 
last four years 
the ruling stems from a suit that challenged rules passed by the 
reagan administration in 1982 
under those regulations if an agency discovers it has overpaid 
someone it normally would seek to deduct the money from future 
checks under the 1982 regulation the amount of the monthly 
deduction money the recipient is not actually getting is 
counted as income in deciding whether the person is eligible for 
supplemental security income to the aged blind or disabled 
velma martin a san leandro railroad workers widow who filed 
the suit had been collecting survivors benefits from the railroad 
retirement board since 1978 and was told by the board in 1985 that 
she had been overpaid more than 8500 over four years because she 
had failed to report additional income 
under its rules the board said it was deducting ms martins 
entire check of 26814 a month for 34 months 
left with only her 386 monthly social security payment as 
income she applied for ssi benefits but was turned down because 
the deducted 26814 was counted as income putting her over the 
eligibility limit 
ms martin then sued and won a ruling by us district judge 
thelton henderson that the 1982 eligibility rules violated federal 
law 
that law defines income as payments received in the form of 
various benefits henderson said both the laws language and intent 
required actual receipt of the money and excluded money that was 
being withheld 
henderson applied his ruling to the entire circuit california 
arizona nevada oregon washington idaho montana alaska and 
hawaii plus guam and the northern marianas 
but the appeals court disagreed with his reading of the law 
under hendersons ruling ssi funds will be used to partially 
subsidize a claimants debt to an outside program said the 
appellate opinion by judge cecil poole 
he said congress would have made its intention clearer if it had 
meant to put such a serious limitation on the governments ability 
to define ssi applicants income 
poole also said ms martin and others whose overpayments came 
from the railroad retirement board could ask the board to spread 
the repayment over a longer period by reducing the monthly 
deductions 
regardless of that option the restrictions cause hardships 
said ms martins lawyer gill deford of the national senior 
citizens law center 
these are people who are receiving welfare benefits he 
said if the amount is less than theyre entitled to under 
federal law almost by definition its working a hardship 
</TEXT>
