<TEXT>
as they go back to their jobs after the labor 
day weekend many government officials and wall street investment 
managers will be focused on the latest trends in the american work 
force 
a monthly report due friday on the employment situation may well 
give financial policymakers their first latesummer signal on the 
economic outlook for the rest of the year 
the data could serve as an early litmus test in the debate over 
whether a recession lies in wait 
in addition some observers think the figures may play a pivotal 
role in determining the federal reserves next move in setting its 
monetary policy 
of course veteran statisticswatchers always caution that 
numbers for any single month shouldnt be asked to carry too much 
weight 
but any weakness that shows up in the report for august would 
come on the heels of a set of decidedly downbeat readings for july 
when the unemployment rate increased to 55 percent from 52 
percent the month before 
julys employment report indicated a much weaker economy with 
heavy job losses in construction services and manufacturing 
notes the current edition of the merrill lynch market letter 
the july report showed a drop of 57000 in nonfarm payroll 
employment excluding workers employed in connection with the 
federal census merrill lynch analysts observe 
they project a further 30000 decline for august again after 
adjusting for shortterm distortions involving the census 
if there were another sizable increase in the unemployment rate 
it could represent the signal the federal reserve has been awaiting 
to relax its credit policy seeking to foster a drop in interest 
rates 
but some analysts warn against making the assumption that 
interest rates would automatically fall as evidence accumulated of 
a business slump 
one widely publicized xfactor in the equation is the august 
surge in world oil prices which has intensified fears of inflation 
in many of the industrialized countries 
in this kind of environment said paul boltz financial 
economist at t rowe price associates in baltimore easing may 
redouble the markets concerns about the feds willingness to fight 
inflation 
the pressure on oil prices eased in the past week permitting 
stock prices to rally the dow jones average of 30 industrials 
closed friday at 261436 up 8144 from the week before 
the new york stock exchange composite index rose 592 to 17697 
the nasdaq composite index for the overthecounter market gained 
1388 to 38121 and the american stock exchange market value index 
was up 710 at 32339 
volume on the big board came to 12788 million shares a day 
down from 18986 million the week before 
even with cooperation from oil prices a good many observers say 
they have reservations about the interestrate outlook 
the us credit markets face stiff competition these days from 
interestbearing securities in other countries such as germany 
where rates are comparable and reported inflation is less 
there are worries too about worldwide demand for capital 
given intense needs for investment in eastern europe 
it also appears that demands to maintain a military presence 
in the middle east will absorb capital the middle east could have 
invested in foreign economies and markets said greg smith at 
prudentialbache securities 
we want to be somewhat cautious about assuming interest rates 
will come down any time soon smith concluded even if the 
economy does prove to be as weak as people expect 
</TEXT>
