<TEXT>
airline industry officials say theyre not sure 
what can be done to assure customers get faster ticket service than 
what they encountered earlier this week in a lastminute rush for 
discounted air fares 
when many travel agents around the country tried to lock in 
tickets for airline customers on wednesday their computers spit 
back this message system unavailable 
a deadline for cheap autumn fares combined with a new charge for 
higher jet fuel costs threw the nations airline reservation system 
into what agents and airlines described as an unprecedented 
gridlock 
as tens of thousands of americans jammed phone lines seeking to 
book tickets computers were so slow that getting reservation 
information often took 30 minutes or more rather than the usual few 
seconds some systems crashed and wouldbe passengers who tried 
calling airlines directly wound up on what seemed like permanent 
hold 
the systems not built to handle armageddon and wednesday was 
armageddon dexter koehl spokesman for minneapolisbased carlson 
travel network said friday people simply got shut out 
its unknown how many customers couldnt buy the discounted 
tickets but airlines said passengers had plenty of advance notice 
and shouldnt have waited until the last minute 
industry officials mostly threw up their hands and said there 
was little that could be done to avoid such days in the future 
they said increasing the capacity of airline reservation systems 
has never been discussed because the computers never faced such 
large demand 
but some agents said two prior extensions by airlines of the 
midnight deadline wednesday may have encouraged travelers to take a 
chance and hope for another extension before making plans that 
also may have added to the burden 
the double whammy was a deadline for special fares described 
as among the best deals in recent years with prices discounted 40 
percent or more and a 53 percent fuel surcharge on all tickets 
travel agents worked well into the night to meet demand and 
airlines including northwest airlines american airlines and trans 
world airlines extended the deadline 
we ended up hand writing a lot of tickets said a west coast 
travel agent who asked not to be named im sure we missed a lot 
of calls where we could help people 
usair spokeswoman susan young said the airline received about 
330000 telephone calls on wednesday about 100000 more than 
normal it refused to extend the deadline 
we gave people plenty of time and plenty of notice young 
said there was adequate time people who did hang on the line 
were able to make reservations 
americans sabre airline reservations network with 125000 
terminals handled 100 million entries requesting information on 
wednesday about 25 percent more than the previous singleday 
record 
the airline added a midnight to 6 am shift of agents after 
realizing that thousands of callers probably werent getting 
through and it honored the cheap rates until that time 
i dont know what else we could have done in this case 
american spokesman tim smith said the fares were there for 
almost three weeks we always urge people to plan ahead 
northwest spokesman doug miller said the airline extended the 
cheap fares for 24 hours because people who under normal 
circumstances would have had plenty of time to make the booking 
werent able to 
our computer reservation system was overloaded we were 
experiencing delays in getting bookings accomplished he said 
the fares were good enough to fight for despite busy signals and 
onhold elevator music a midweek roundtrip flight between new york 
and charlotte nc was 158 under the special fare compared to 
251 now a new york to los angeles ticket was 318 until 
wednesday now 449 
carlson travel network which has 1300 offices nationwide said 
its air sales in the first three days of the week as the deadline 
bulge grew were 39 million compared with 30 million for the 
previous seven days 
at one carlson agency in midtown manhattan the manager stayed 
until 330 am thursday processing tickets the company is busy 
calculating its overtime costs for the week 
its like when you flip on every switch in the house 
susannah knight owner of knight travel in charlotte said of the 
overload they more or less blew a fuse 
</TEXT>
