<TEXT>
gasoline prices have surged to their highest levels in years 
but they arent keeping many americans home this labor day weekend 
fueladdicted motorists seem willing to pay whatever they must 
even though the inflated prices have some folks grumbling at the 
pump 
its like being in jail said bud case a builder from south 
charleston wva if the bail is 10000 someone will dig in and 
get that money gas prices are the same way 
as case shelled out 2613 to fill up his chevy s10 camper 
friday in charleston he said hed spend 5 a gallon if that was 
what it took to get away for the holiday 
prices arent nearly that bad amid the oil crisis caused by 
iraqs invasion of kuwait although a road trip this weekend will 
cost a few dollars more than it did last labor day 
the american automobile association reported that gasoline 
prices were averaging 1307 for a gallon of selfserve regular 
unleaded just before the long weekend thats up from 1084 over 
the july 4 holiday and 1062 on labor day last year 
the aaa predicted a 2 percent decrease in labor day travel but 
it said higher gasoline is not to blame 
we think it has more to do with just the general doldrums of 
the economy aaa spokesman geoff sundstrom said historically 
people tend to curtail their travel if theyre concerned about 
their economic livelihood high prices by themselves dont seem to 
cut into travel that much 
motorists interviewed around the nation agreed they are pretty 
much hooked on fuel so theyre using it even if they dont like 
the price 
it ought to be back where it was before they started all this 
foolishness said jacob rogers 84 of belgrade maine as he 
filled his station wagon at north augusta texaco on friday 
i think its terrible but what are you going to do asked 
lewis ashley of raleigh nc gasoline is a necessity people are 
going to drive even if hits 2 a gallon they dont have much of a 
choice 
ashley said he had started riding city buses more in the last 
month because of the increased gasoline prices 
driving 303 miles from st louis to chicago would take 1980 
worth of gas at current prices and an average 20 miles per gallon 
compared with 1642 on july 4 or 1609 last labor day 
cars with better gas mileage would cost less but gas guzzlers 
would cost more 
if people realize that on a relatively short trip that were 
not really talking big bucks it shouldnt stop them from going 
said bern rotman spokesman for the new york state department of 
economic development his department estimated a labor day round 
trip of 600 miles will cost just 532 more than it did last year 
people have planned their labor day trip and theyre taking 
it said frank eastvedt spokesman for the automobile club of 
southern california 
the club has noticed changes in the types of vacations people 
are taking 
were doing more short trips than longer ones he said 
theyre taking maybe trips just within the state rather than 
going further 
a survey in alabama found motorists are avoiding the 
fullservice lanes and pumping their own gas often they switch to 
cheaper grades 
