<TEXT>
hundreds of union workers at chrysler corp have 
accepted buyouts designed to reduce the no 3 automakers need for 
layoffs 
the workers punched out for the last time friday chrysler 
spokesman lee sechler estimated about 600 people had signed up for 
the buyout program 
its a positive alternative to layoffs he said 
the reduction in the companys work force comes as chrysler 
negotiates a new national labor contract with the united auto 
workers union and as the financially struggling company seeks ways 
to cut costs 
meantime negotiators for the uaw and general motors corp 
continued meetings friday in subcommittees that focus on particular 
contract issues such as wages benefits and job security 
last tuesday the union picked gm as its bargaining target 
intending to reach an agreement that it can then bring to the other 
two automakers contracts covering more than 450000 active workers 
for gm chrysler and ford motor co expire sept 14 
gm and uaw officials said they planned to meet during the labor 
day weekend negotiations began in midjuly 
sechler said it wont be known until late next week or perhaps 
later how much money the automaker is spending on the buyout he 
declined to provide details of the plan which is contained in a 
1988 national uawchrysler contract 
the payout formula is based primarily on an eligible workers 
seniority with chrysler there are about 60000 uawcovered 
employees at chrysler but company and union officials said they 
didnt know precisely how many of them would be eligible for the 
program 
the plans is not open to workers in some chrysler factories 
such as its jeep assembly plant in toledo and some job 
classifications within plants such as skilled trades 
chrysler is involved in a costcutting program launched last 
october to slice 15 billion from its 26 billion annual budget by 
the end of this year 
the automakers secondquarter earnings were down 472 percent 
and chrysler has acknowledged that the company will post a 
significant loss during the third quarter mainly because of 
production interruptions at its profitable minivan plants 
production at the minivan factories in st louis and windsor 
ontario was stopped for about four weeks to retool for 1991 models 
since reaching its 1988 contract with the uaw chrysler has shut 
down two assembly plants in kenosha wis and detroit resulting 
in more than 7000 layoffs chrysler plans to close its st louis 
car plant nov 9 
meantime an unidentified uaw official was harshly critical of 
chrysler in a story in friday editions of the detroit news for 
reinstating merit pay for executives while pleading poverty to 
hourly workers 
sechler said an inhouse magazine distributed to employees in 
april noted that the meritpay program had been reinstated after 
being suspended last october when the costcutting program began 
</TEXT>
